The '''Genealogical Proof Standard''' ('''GPS''') is a guideline for establishing the reliability ("proof") of a [[Genealogy|genealogical]] conclusion with reasonable certainty.  It is important within the genealogical community for clearly communicating the quality of research performed, such as by a professional genealogist.  It is also useful for helping new genealogists understand what is needed to do high-quality research.

It has five elements:
* a reasonably exhaustive research;
* complete and accurate source [[citation]]s;
* analysis and correlation of the collected information;
* resolution of any conflicting [[evidence]]; and
* a soundly reasoned, coherently written conclusion.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Board for Certification of Genealogists ® - The Genealogical Proof Standard|url = http://www.bcgcertification.org/resources/standard.html|website = www.bcgcertification.org|access-date = 2016-02-20}}</ref>

