{{unreferenced|date=August 2012}} {{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Letters to Judy: What Kids Wish They Could Tell You | title_orig = | translator = | image = Image:Letters to Judy What Kids Wish They Could Tell You book cover2.jpg | caption = First edition | author = [[Judy Blume]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | genre = | publisher = [[G. P. Putnam's Sons|Putnam]] | release_date = [[1986 in literature|1986]] | english_release_date = | media_type = Print | pages = | isbn = 0-399-13129-9 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} {{Portal |Children's literature}}
'''''Letters to Judy: What Kids Wish They Could Tell You''''' is a book published by [[Judy Blume]] in [[1986 in literature|1986]]. It is not a novel, but a collection of letters from children with responses from Blume.
Blume quotes correspondence she receives asking for advice, written by readers of her [[children's books]], boys and girls who feel unable to confide in their parents. The letters come from youngsters 10 years old through the teens and tell about specific problems most of which Blume has addressed in her novels. Some of these kids are loners rejected by peers; others feel neglected at home or hurt by [[divorce]]. A divorced mother herself, Blume is sympathetic to the young people who write to her and sympathizes with parents as well; she intends this book to help them become more aware of their children's needs.
